**1\. Introduction**

**Dataset :  https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/flynn28/european-football-matches**

Background/Context  
Being the most popular sport, football is no longer purely a sport but also an economy. The value in the football business is enormous, with gambling on football contributing a large portion. In 2023 to 2024, the amount of football betting in Hong Kong reached 160 billion HKD(Hong Kong Jockey Club, n.d.) .  
Football goals are relatively rare, discrete events, making the Poisson distribution a natural fit for modelling score outcomes(Paul Trevor,2024). In this report, I am going to use this statistical model to predict scores and apply different approaches to improve accuracy.

Motivation  
In Football Gambling, there are lots of bets options,such as the result( Home win, draw, Away win), and number of goals, corner kicks , but the highest odds is the exact scoreline of the game, which indicates that the probability of getting the correct score is the lowest(Tochukwu Richard ,2025) . Since the minimum odds for exact scorelines are typically around 6.0, an accuracy of at least 17% is required to make a positive expected return in the long run(Aussportsbetting.com, n.d.). 

Proposed Solution  
This project investigates whether refining the estimation of λ in the Poisson distribution and applying different data preprocessing ,such as number of Matches counted, excluding different extreme cases, can significantly improve prediction accuracy of football match scores over traditional average-based approaches.

Contributions

1. Developed and implemented a Poisson-based score prediction framework with three λ estimation methods and four preprocessing pipelines.  
2. Designed a method to construct seasonal labels and filter out irrelevant or extreme match data.  
3. Evaluated model performance across leagues and seasons, revealing insights into the effectiveness of regression-based and simple mean approaches in real-world football data.

**Research Methodology**

The dataset I’m using is from [https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/flynn28/european-football-matches](https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/flynn28/european-football-matches), which contains 22 sub-datasets and a combined set. Each sub-dataset is a record of a European football league from 1993 (some leagues start from 1994 or 1996\) to 2023\. The combined set includes all subsets and contains a total of 216,883 recorded matches. The dataset has 7 features:

● League: Showing where the data comes from

● Date: Showing when the match was played

● Home Team: Showing the team playing at home

● Away Team: Showing the team playing away

● Home Goals: Showing the number of goals the home team scored, one of the most important features

● Away Goals: Showing the number of goals the away team scored, another very important feature 

● Result: Showing which team, home or away, won the game, or if it was a draw 

Sub-Dataset Checking 

In this stage, I checked each dataset to see any missing data, and found that 6 sub-datasets had issues; therefore, they were dropped: Greek Super League (missing records from 2000–2005), Belgian Jupiler League (missing records in some seasons), Scottish Division 1 (only 10 teams, too little data), Scottish Division 2 (only 10 teams, too little data), Scottish Division 3 (only 10 teams, too little data) ,English Conference League(Missing records in some season)

Data PreProcessing 

As I want to show the results of each season, I had to create another feature called ‘Season’. In most European countries, the football league starts in August and ends in May or June the next year. Therefore, it is not appropriate to look only at the ‘Date’ feature to determine the season. The logic I used to form this new feature is simple: as the dataset is in chronological order and the number of matches (N) is fixed for each season, I classified the first N matches as Season 1, the second N matches as Season 2, and so on. However, in some leagues, the number of teams increased, such as Italy’s Serie A: from 1993 to 2003 it had only 18 teams, and from 2004 it increased to 20 teams. Also, during COVID, some leagues were shortened (Davies and Dunbar, 2022), such as in Eredivisie, Holland, where 2019–2020 had only 274 matches. Therefore, a different formula is used for different matches.

Feature Engineering 

Next I created 4 different Feature Engineering approach(DF , DF2 , DF3, DF4 )

DF : The original dataset, nothing changed

DF2 : removed extreme case: goals \> 5 , From the combined dataset, we can see that in most of the matches the home or away goals are below 5 , why 5 ? because according to the Fig 1, most of the game are less than 5 goals .sometimes removing outliers doesn’t improve the model, especially when the outlier is not caused by a wrong data entry (Goyal, 2021\) 

DF3 : removed that new promoted team of the season, In European leagues, usually the bottom 2 or 3 teams of tier 1 will be relegated to tier 2 in the next season, and the top 3 teams in tier 2 will be promoted to tier 1\. In DF3, I removed those teams which were newly promoted/relegated, as they were not present in the league in the last season, and their data is irrelevant

DF4 : Combine both DF2 and DF3

Finding the Best window for Rolling average

One of the most important objectives is finding how many past matches should be used to compute the λ, in this part , 5 different numbers are used to test. We tried 10, 20, 30, 40, 50\. To keep the fairness for all 5 different numbers , we skipped the first 3 rd season, for example, if the dataset starts in 1993, we will start with using the 1996-1997 season in this part to make sure there are enough matches.

Finding the approach for the λ

In Poisson Distribution, λ is the most important parameter and it will affect the accuracy very much. In this part , I used 3 ways to find the λ and examine the performance.

Simple Mean Approach:  Compute λ\_home as the mean home goals for the home team over the last N games, and λ\_away as the mean away goals for the away team over the last N. 

Multi (Attack × Defense) Approach : Modified the approach by  Ryansst (2024) , which estimate home attack (home team’s recent home goals) and away defense (goals the away team recently conceded away), and set  
λ\_home \= (home attack) × (away defense); similarly,  
λ\_away \= (away attack) × (home defense).  
This incorporates both teams’ offensive and defensive form, making λ opponent-aware while staying simple. Ryansst ( 2024\) also included the overall average home and away goals from all teams , but I erased this part. 

Regression-Based (Rolling) Approach: Fit Poisson regressions on a rolling window with team dummies and a home-advantage term to predict λ\_home and λ\_away. This captures relative attack or defense strengths across teams and adapts to opponents, offering a more structural estimate than raw averages

Accuracy improvement using the low score adjustment

After find out the best approach, we run another model to see if the accuracy .Because football is predominantly low-scoring and low-score outcomes (0–0, 1–1) show extra dependence, the standard independent Poisson model often underestimates draws; Dixon & Coles (1997)  adjustment addresses this.
